1) Key features of Wi-Fi 6, 6E, and 7 vs Wi-Fi 5
Wi-Fi 5 (802.11ac)
5 GHz only
MU-MIMO (downlink only)
No OFDMA


Wi-Fi 6 (802.11ax)
OFDMA (uplink + downlink)
Longer OFDMA symbol duration
1024 QAM
MU-MIMO (UL + DL)
BSS Coloring (spatial reuse) and OBSS-PD
Target Wake Time (TWT)
Better efficiency in dense networks
Trigger Based Random Access
Improved Aggregation and Scheduling


Wi-Fi 6E
Same as Wi-Fi 6 + 6 GHz band
Less interference
More spectral effciency


Wi-Fi 7 (802.11be)
Multi-Link Operation (MLO)
320 MHz channels
4K-QAM
Preamble Puncturing
rTWT
Dynamic OFDMA Scheduling
Smarter Aggregation and Retransmission
Extremely low latency with short guard intervals



2) Role of OFDMA in Wi-Fi 6
OFDMA divides a channel into Resource Units (RUs)
Role:
Multiple users transmit simultaneously
AP schedules users dynamically

Process:
AP schedules trigger frames to control uplink access.
The STA that didn't access the channel use the Resource Units


Benefits:
Reduced latency
Better efficiency
Less contention
Ideal for IoT and dense networks



3) Target Wake Time (TWT)
 Power-saving mechanism in which STA and AP negotiate on time slots when the STA will be active to receive data for transmission.
How:
AP schedules when device wakes up
Device sleeps rest of the time

Process:
1.TWT Request
2.TWT Agreement
3.STA sleep and wake at agreed times

Benefits:
Battery saving
Reduced contention
Better network efficiency


