Uses multiple bands simultaneously
2.4+5+6 GHz
Impact:
Higher throughput
Lower latency
Redundancy (failover)

Example:
Device uses 5 GHz + 6 GHz at same time

8) Purpose of 802.11k and 802.11v

802.11k (Radio Resource Management)
Provides:
Neighbor reports (list of nearby APs)

802.11v (BSS transition)
Helps:
AP suggests better AP to client
Benefit:
Faster roaming decisions



9) Fast BSS Transition (802.11r)
Reduces roaming delay

How:
Pre-authentication
Key caching

Benefit:
Seamless roaming (important for VoIP)
Efficient in dense networks
Enhanced UX in enterprise and public Wifi


10) How 802.11k/v/r work together

Combined workflow:
Step 1 (802.11k):
Client gets list of nearby APs

Step 2 (802.11v):
AP recommends best AP

Step 3 (802.11r):
Fast authentication during handoff

Result:
Fast + seamless roaming with minimal delay

